  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad consensus that money laundering is against the law in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages: placement (introducing the illicit funds into the financial system), layering (concealing the source of the funds through complex transactions), and integration (reintroducing the now \"clean\" money into the economy).\n\nMost countries have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF). These laws require financial institutions and other entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities, conduct customer due diligence, and maintain records of transactions.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Additionally, international cooperation has increased, with countries working together to trace and seize illicit funds across borders.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely recognized as a criminal activity, and there is a strong global consensus on the need to combat it through comprehensive legal frameworks and international cooperation.",
